elements.content: The use of dipyrido[3,2-d:2‘,3‘-f]quinoxaline (Dpq) combined with three structurally related benzene-dicarboxylic acid ligands [benzene-1,3-dicarboxylic acid (H2 L ), benzene-1,2-dicarboxylic acid (H2 L ), and biphenyl-4,4‘-dicarboxylic acid (H2 L )] has allowed the rational design of three novel Cd(II) coordination polymers, [Cd3(Dpq)3(L 1 )3]·4.5H2O (1), [Cd(Dpq)(L 2 )(H2O)] (2), and [Cd2(Dpq)2(L 3 )2]·1.5H2O (3), which were hydrothermally synthesized and structurally determined by X-ray analysis. Compound 1 features a 1-D ribbonlike structure, compound 2 shows novel 2-D four-connected networks, and compound 3 possesses an interesting 6-connected 2-fold interpenetrated 3-D α-Po-related architecture. The Dpq ligand takes a chelating coordination mode while the other two nitrogen atoms did not coordinate to the Cd(II) ions. In these complexes, the three benzene−dicarboxylate ligands are able to link Cd(II) ions in various coordination modes, giving rise to 1-, 2-, and 3-dimensional Cd complexes, respectively. In addition, complexes 1 − 3 exhibit blue/green emission in the solid state at room temperature.

Introduction

The past decade has seen remarkable progress in the development of new materials based on transition-metal ions and organic ligands, often termed as coordination polymers (networks) or metal-organic frameworks. These metal-organic materials can be rationally synthesized and tuned by a suitable choice of organic ligands and metal ions to control their framework architecture and functionality. However, recent reviews on the framework topologies and other geometrical characteristics of network solids reflect that it remains a challenge to achieve a true advance without understanding the structural aspects of such materials at a molecular or an atomic resolution. In this regard, the skillful combination of bridging carboxylates, 2,2‘-bipyridyl-like (bpy-like) chelating ligands, and metal ions has generated many interesting coordination architectures. Unfortunately, owing to the termination effect of chelating bpy-like ligands, such coordination polymers containing both polycarboxylates and bpy-like ligands are usually only one-dimensional (1-D) and two-dimensional (2-D) coordination polymers. As far as we know, high dimensional and connected complexes based on benzene-dicarboxylate and bpy-like ligands have rarely been reported. Moreover, luminescent organic compounds and metal-organic coordination polymers have been an active research area for decades because of their various potential applications in material science, in which stable luminescent metal-organic coordination polymers that are useful in electroluminescent devices are still not common and still challenging to prepare.

elements.content: As shown above, benzene−dicarboxylate ligands and metal−Dpq coordination can furnish different dimensional coordination polymers. The V-shaped L 1 ligands in 1 coordinated to adjacent Cd(II) ions to form a parallelogram metal cluster in a shoulder-to-shoulder fashion, leading to the formation of ribbonlike framework of 1. The nonlinear benzene−dicarboxylate L 2 generates a 2-D architecture in 2. The most critical factor for the polyermic layer is presumed to be the geometry and flexibility of the benzene−dicarboxylate ligand of L 2 . Interestingly, the long and linear benzene−dicarboxylate ligand L 3 in 3 is twisted in such a way that the two phenyl rings form a dihedral angle of 31.10°. This in turn leads to the slanted orientation of the Dpq ligand to the Cd(II) ions (ca. 60°, compared with tetranuclear Cd planar) and the formation of 3. In contrast with L 3 , the benzene−dicarboxylate ligands L 1 and L 2 are very rigid and cannot twist; hence, the Dpq ligands in 1 and 2 are oriented almost vertical to the chain or planar and act as terminal ligands occupying one coordinate direction and, thus, in a way are unfavorable for the formation of 3-D coordination polymers. On the other hand, the presence of the larger aromatic Dpq ligand (compared with bpy and phen) further enhances the aromatic stacking interactions, and thus results in the formation of supramolecular structures 1 and 2. These observations strongly suggest the length and flexibility of the benzene−dicarboxylate ligands are essential for the predicted results. Therefore, an appropriate combination of the benzene−dicarboxylate and aromatic chelating ligands is critical to the formation of high dimensional structures.

elements.content: Photoluminescence Properties. The solid-state fluorescence spectra of 1 − 3 at room temperature are depicted in Figure . Free Dpq ligand also fluoresces in the solid state with two main emission peaks at 436 and 562 nm upon excitation at 360 nm (Figure , inset). As shown in Figure , complex 2 exhibits one red shift (455 nm) and one blue shift (530 nm) shoulder emission band peak (λex = 401 nm) with respect to free Dpq ligand. As previously reported, solid-state benzene−dicarboxylate ligands, L 1 −L 3 , can also exhibit fluorescence at room temperature, and the emission bands of these ligands can be assigned to the π* → n transition. Fluorescent emission of benzene-dicarboxylate ligands resulting from the π* → n transition is very weak compared with that of the π* → π transition of the Dpq ligand, so L 1 −L 3 ligands almost have no contribution to the fluorescent emission of as-synthesized polymers. Accordingly, the main emission band of 2 would be assigned to π* → π transition of coordinated Dpq ligands. The red shift emission peak probably is related to the intraligand fluorescent emission, and similar red shifts have been observed before. The blue shift shoulder peak at ca. 530 nm compared with that of the free Dpq at 562 nm may therefore be attributed to the chelating of the Dpq ligand to the metal ion (LMCT), which effectively increases the rigidity of the ligand and reduces the loss of energy by radiationless decay of the intraligand emission excited state. The emission peak position of 3 (ca. 454 nm, λex = 405 nm) is similar to the red shift peak of complex 2 that also can be attributed to intraligand fluorescent emission. Interestingly, the main green emission band of 1, ranging from 450 to 650 nm with a peak at ca. 505 nm (λex = 447 nm), is obviously different from that of 2 and 3. It would be probably assigned to ligand-to-metal charge transfer (LMCT) and/or the intraligand fluorescent emission. The different emission bands of 1, 2, and 3 may be due to the significant difference of their topological structure because the fluorescence behavior is closely associated with the metal ions and the ligands coordinated around them. These observations indicate that compounds 1, 2, and 3 may be excellent candidates of blue/green-light photoactive materials, since these condensed materials are highly thermally stable and insoluble in common polar and nonpolar solvents.

Conclusion

Three novel Cd complexes have been synthesized under hydrothermal conditions exhibiting a systematic variation of architecture by the employment of three structurally related benzene-dicarboxylate ligands, and representing examples of structural changes from the 1-D coordination complex to a 3-D coordination polymeric network based on bi-, tri-, and tetranuclear structural units. Three structurally related benzene-dicarboxylate ligands give rise to a systematic structural variation in the presence of the bpy-like chelating ligand dipyrido[3,2-d:2‘,3‘-f]quinoxaline by hydrogen bonds and π-π stacking interactions, which implies a potential tool for crystal engineering. Furthermore, the strong fluorescent properties of complexes 1, 2, and 3 may make them excellent candidates for potential photoactive materials.
